AirAsia, Ayala Land, Formosa Plastics, TSMC: Asia Ex-Japan Equity Preview

-- B y   B e r n i   M o e s t a f a
-- 
2011-08-09T21:46:24Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-09/airasia-ayala-land-formosa-plastics-tsmc-asia-ex-japan-equity-preview.html
The following companies may have
unusual price changes today in Asian trading, excluding  Japan .
Stock symbols are in parentheses, and share prices are from the
previous close, unless noted otherwise.  AirAsia Bhd. (AIRA)  : AirAsia’s biggest shareholder
agreed to swap a 10 percent stake in  Asia ’s largest low-cost
carrier for 20.5 percent of  Malaysian Airline System Bhd. (MAS)  , forging ties between the nation’s two biggest carriers.
Tune Air Sdn. will trade shares with government-controlled
Khazanah Nasional Bhd., according to a joint statement by the
companies. AirAsia last traded at 3.95 ringgit before it was
suspended on Aug. 8. Malaysian Air last traded at 1.60 ringgit
before its share suspension.  Ayala Land Inc. (ALI)  : The  Philippines ’ largest builder
said first-half profit rose 35 percent to 3.38 billion pesos
($79.6 million) as home sales and rental earnings increased.
Revenue in the January to June period increased 15 percent to
21.25 billion pesos. Ayala dropped 4.5 percent to 15 pesos.  Formosa Plastics Corp. (1301)  (1301 TT): The Taiwanese plastic
material manufacturer may gain NT$109 million ($3.8 million)
from selling real estate in Kaohsiung, southern  Taiwan , for
NT$647 million, the company said in a statement to the local
stock exchange. Formosa Plastics slid 0.8 percent to NT$83.60.  Hong Kong Aircraft Engineering Co. (44 HK): The aircraft
maintenance company posted first-half net income of HK$425
million, according to a statement to the Hong Kong stock
exchange. Hong Kong Aircraft dropped 3.4 percent to HK$100.50.  Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing Co. (2330 TT): The
world’s largest custom manufacturer of chips bought NT$537
million of equipment from Novellus Systems International B.V.
from April 13 to Aug. 9, the Hsinchu, Taiwan-based company said
in a statement to the stock exchange. Taiwan Semiconductor fell
2.9 percent to NT$63.30.  TDM Bhd. (TDM)  : The Malaysian palm-oil producer said
second-quarter net income more than doubled from a year earlier
to 32 million ringgit ($10.6 million), according to a company
statement. The stock fell 3.1 percent to 2.84 ringgit.  Yung Kong Galvanizing Industries Bhd. (YKGI MK): The
Malaysian manufacturer of steel products withdrew its
application to list its Starshine Holdings Bhd. unit because of
the “current market conditions” and pending further
reorganization of the group, according to a company statement.
The stock slid 2.2 percent to 44 sen.  To contact the reporter on this story:
